# No Hardcoded Examples or Client Data in UI Copy

## The Problem This Rule Exists To Fix

UI modals, tooltips, placeholders, and helper text were shipping with:

- Real client names as placeholder examples (`companionscpas`, `fuelnfreetime`, etc.)
- Internal path structures hardcoded into visible strings (`brand/{projectId}/`)
- Platform internals exposed as UI suggestions (`work-context + project row`, `Cloudflare bindings via D1`)

This is a privacy violation, a professionalism failure, and it will not ship.

---

## Rule 1: Zero Real Names in UI Copy

**Never** use a real client name, project slug, domain, or internal identifier as an example, placeholder, default value, or suggestion in any user-facing string.

This includes:

- `placeholder="e.g. companionscpas"`
- `hint="e.g. fuelnfreetime or pawlove"`
- `label="like proj_agentsam_sdk"`
- Any string containing a real slug, tenant ID, project ID, or client name

**Correct pattern — use purely fictional, obviously-generic examples:**

```tsx
// ✅
placeholder="e.g. my-project or acme-corp"
placeholder="e.g. acme or widget-co"
hint="Use a short, lowercase identifier"

// ❌
placeholder="e.g. companionscpas or fuelnfreetime"
placeholder="e.g. proj_agentsam_sdk"
```

---

## Rule 2: No Platform Internals in Notification/Modal Copy

Modal descriptions, toast messages, and inline helper text must never expose:

- Table names (`D1`, `agentsam_*`, internal binding names)
- Route paths (`/api/projects/work-context`, `Cloudflare bindings via D1`)
- Internal resolution logic ("Auto resolves bucket from /api/projects/work-context")
- Storage keys or prefixes visible to the end user

If the user needs to understand *what* something does, describe the outcome — not the mechanism.

**Correct pattern:**

```tsx
// ✅
"Storage location for this project. Defaults to your workspace bucket."
"Connected storage bucket for this project."

// ❌
"Saved in this browser first. Auto resolves bucket from /api/projects/work-context
(Cloudflare bindings via D1) — no hardcoded client routes."
"Source Auto (work-context + project row) → R2 bucket override"
```

---

## Rule 3: Project Connections Use a Connections Dropdown, Not Text

Each project in the dashboard represents a real build with real service connections (Cloudflare Workers, GitHub repos, Supabase, Stripe, etc.). These connections must be displayed as a **Connections dropdown/panel** with provider icons — never as hardcoded text, placeholder suggestions, or inline copy.

Implementation requirements:

- Render a `<ConnectionsDropdown projectId={projectId} />` component
- Show provider icons (Cloudflare, GitHub, Supabase, Stripe, Resend, etc.) resolved dynamically from the project's actual integration registry
- Empty state: "No connections configured" — never list fake or example connections
- Do not expose internal binding names (`DB`, `R2`, `KV`, `HYPERDRIVE`) as the display label — use the integration's `display_name` from the registry

```tsx
// ✅ — dynamic, icon-driven, real data only
<ConnectionsDropdown projectId={project.id} />

// ❌ — hardcoded, exposes internals, leaks client data
<span>e.g. companionscpas or iKey prefix brand/{projectId}/</span>
<span>Cloudflare R2 · D1 · GitHub</span> // hardcoded, not from registry
```

---

## Rule 4: Placeholder Text Must Be Generic and Fictional

Any `placeholder`, `hint`, `description`, `helperText`, or `example` string must use **obviously fictional, non-client-specific** values. When in doubt, use these safe defaults:

| Context | Safe placeholder |
|---|---|
| Project name | `my-project`, `acme-app` |
| Slug / key prefix | `acme`, `widget-co` |
| Domain | `example.com`, `myapp.io` |
| Email | `hello@example.com` |
| Org / team | `my-team`, `acme-corp` |
| API key | `sk_...` or `[hidden]` |
| Bucket / storage | `my-bucket` |
| Worker name | `my-worker` |

Never derive placeholder text from actual data in the codebase, database, or environment.

---

## Rule 5: Logs, Errors, and Bindings Are Exempt

Real values ARE acceptable in:

- Developer console logs
- Error stack traces
- Wrangler binding names in `wrangler.jsonc`
- Internal debug panels gated behind superadmin/dev flags
- CI/CD output

This rule applies exclusively to **user-facing UI copy**: modals, tooltips, placeholders, notifications, onboarding text, helper descriptions, and any string a non-developer end user will read.

---

## Enforcement Checklist Before Shipping Any Modal/Notification/Tooltip

- [ ] Does any string contain a real client name, project slug, or tenant ID? → Remove it
- [ ] Does any string expose an internal route, table name, or binding? → Replace with outcome description
- [ ] Does any placeholder use a real name from the codebase or DB? → Replace with fictional generic
- [ ] Are project connections shown as icons from the registry, not hardcoded text? → Verify dropdown renders live data
- [ ] Would a user seeing this string learn anything about another tenant's data or our internal architecture? → If yes, rewrite it

If any checkbox fails, the component does not ship.
